                </a></li></ul></div><p><strong>Figure 5.  <span>Germline SXL is necessary for expression of the female-specific <em>Rm62</em> transcript.</span></strong></p><a id="article1.body1.sec2.sec6.fig1.caption1.p1" name="article1.body1.sec2.sec6.fig1.caption1.p1"></a><p>A. XX flies homozygous for the <em>snf<sup>1621</sup></em> or <em>snf<sup>148</sup></em> alleles, which disrupt SXL function specifically in the germline, do not express the female-specific <em>Rm62</em> transcript (lanes 1 and 3). Expression of a <em>Sxl</em> cDNA in <em>snf</em> mutant backgrounds under the control of the <em>otu</em> promoter restores the synthesis of the female-specific <em>Rm62</em> transcript (lanes 2 and 4). B. XX flies homozygous for the <em>Sxl<sup>f4</sup></em> or <em>Sxl<sup>f5</sup></em> alleles show a loss of the female-specific <em>Rm62</em> transcript (lanes 3 and 4). C. The female-specific <em>Rm62</em> transcript is maternally deposited, and is present only in mature ovaries.</p>
